          From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia                            Jump to:     navigation,      search             1895 in South Africa    1892 1893 1894 « 1895 » 1896 1897 1898          List of years in South Africa       Contents   1 Events 2 Births 3 Deaths 4 Railways  4.1 Railway lines opened 4.2 Locomotives   5 References    Events[edit]  April   13 – The first electrical street lights in Cape Town are switched on.   June   11 – Britain annexes Tongaland, between Zululand and Mozambique.   December   15 – The railways of the Cape Colony, Natal, the Orange Free State, the South African Republic and southern Mozambique are all linked at Union Junction near Alberton, completing the logistics supply lines for the British military invasion of the Boer Republics in the Second Boer War.[1] 29 – The Jameson Raid is launched when Leander Starr Jameson and his forces cross into Transvaal from Bechuanaland.   Unknown date   St. Lucia Game Reserve, 30 km north of the town St. Lucia is proclaimed. The Hluhluwe Game Reserve is proclaimed. The Umfolozi Game Reserve is proclaimed.  Births[edit]    This section is empty. You can help by adding to it. (July 2010)   Deaths[edit]    This section is empty. You can help by adding to it. (December 2013)   Railways[edit] Railway lines opened[edit]  1 December – Natal – Charlestown to Natal-Transvaal border, 2 miles 45 chains (4.1 kilometres).[1] 15 December – Transvaal – Natal-Transvaal border to Union Junction near Alberton, 157 miles (252.7 kilometres).[1]  Locomotives[edit]  Pauling and Company places the first of forty-two 4-4-0 American type 2 ft (610 mm) narrow gauge locomotives in service on the Beira Railway in Mozambique. In 1915 thirteen of these locomotives, later classified Class NG6 on the SAR, will be acquired by the Union Defence Force for use in South Africa to replace locomotives that will be commandeered for the war effort in German South West Africa during World War I.[2][3][4]  References[edit]   ^ a b c S